observations.recommendation:
We strongly reiterated that the Mayor direct the:
a. Treasurer’s Office/Inventory Committee to hasten the completion of the inventory count of all the property, plant and equipment and exert more effort to reconcile their records on PPE and conduct an in depth analysis of PPE accounts.
b. Treasurer’s Office/Inventory Committee to apply more time to identify the unaccounted/unclassified properties amounting to P54,373,083.56 and effect needed reconciliation on either records;
c. Treasurer’s Office/Inventory Committee to expedite the process by which the unserviceable properties could be disposed of, in accordance with the aforecited rules and regulations, so that the balances of Property, Plant and Equipment accounts presented in the financial statements would only represent those assets that are in existence and servicing the needs of the Municipality;
d. Treasurer’s Office/Inventory Committee to use and submit the prescribed, properly accomplished and approved Report on Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) and prepare separate RPCPPE for each PPE account;
e. the Accounting Office to submit to COA the Journal Entry Vouchers (JEVs) and other supporting documents used as basis of adjustments/reclassifications made on the PPE amounting to P36,301,790.68; and
f. the Accounting Office to review the account titles used in the preparation of the financial statement and properly use only the prescribed chart of accounts under the Philippines Public Sector Accounting Standards.

We reiterated that the Municipal Mayor require the:
• Treasurer’s Office to prepare and maintain road networks property cards and to submit Report on Local Road Network;
• Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;
• Inventory Committee to conduct inventory count of all the Municipality’s road network systems and accordingly submit a Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network System as of the end of the year; and
• Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain the prescribed property ledger cards for Local Road Networks and disclose the information in the Notes to the Financial Statements in accordance with COA Circular 2015-008.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct:
• the mentioned Accountable Officers (AO) under his jurisdiction to submit the lacking supporting documents for the above noted transactions to warrant the regularity of the payments made, otherwise, the transactions will be suspended/disallowed in audit;
• the concerned officials/employees to immediately liquidate their outstanding cash advance otherwise the Audit Team will be constrained to issue a demand letter and eventually advise the former to cause or order the withholding of the payment of any money due the AO;
• the Accountant to coordinate with the DepED Office as to the assignment of the former school head, for the DepEd issuance of demand letter and/or imposition of all available remedies with regards to the latter’s outstanding cash advance.
Henceforth, ensure the proper granting, utilization and liquidation of all cash advances within the prescribed period in accordance with the above-cited rules and regulations.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the Municipal Accountant and the concerned officials/employees to:
• submit the lacking supporting documents for the above noted transactions to warrant the regularity of the payments made, otherwise, the transactions will be suspended/disallowed in audit;
• see to it that brief and concise explanation on the nature of the transactions was correctly stated/properly disclosed in the disbursement vouchers, and;
• Review the completeness of the supporting documents of the disbursement vouchers before the same are paid and ensure compliance with COA Circular No. 2012-001.
